1. Start broad, then narrow

Always begin with:

Protocol filters (tcp, udp, arp, icmp, dns, http)

Then add behavior-based filters

2. Recognize common attack patterns (this is the real skill)
ðŸ” Nmap scans

TCP Connect scan

tcp.flags.syn==1 and tcp.flags.ack==0 and tcp.window_size > 1024


SYN scan

tcp.flags.syn==1 and tcp.flags.ack==0 and tcp.window_size <= 1024


UDP scan

icmp.type==3 and icmp.code==3


ðŸ‘‰ Look for volume + repetition, not single packets.

ðŸ§ª ARP poisoning / MITM

Red flags:

Same IP â†’ multiple MAC addresses

One MAC receiving most traffic

Key filters:

arp
eth.src == <suspicious_mac>
eth.dst == <suspicious_mac>

ðŸ” Credential sniffing (HTTP)

Focus on:

POST requests

application/x-www-form-urlencoded

Filters:

http.request.method == POST
urlencoded-form contains "user"
urlencoded-form contains "pass"

ðŸ§¬ Host & user identification

Use protocol metadata:

DHCP â†’ hostname

NBNS â†’ workstation names

Kerberos â†’ users & hosts

Examples:

dhcp.option.hostname
nbns.name
kerberos.CNameString

ðŸš¨ DNS / ICMP tunneling

What matters:

Long subdomains

High volume

Encoded-looking strings

DNS:

dns and strlen(dns.qry.name) > 50


ICMP:

Large payloads

Repeating ICMP traffic after execution

Analyst mindset (this matters more than filters)

Ask yourself:

Is this normal behavior for this protocol?

Is there volume, repetition, or odd structure?

Does it happen after another suspicious event?
